inexorable.definition: Impossible to prevent or stop; inevitable.
inexorable.example1: The seemingly inexorable rise of Pepsi—which had also been so clearly signaled by market research—never materialized either.
inexorable.example2: Most of the time, I could forget about it, but the inexorable truth is this: They might be glad to have me around, but I was the alpha and the omega of my parents’ suffering.
inexorable.example3: The bush fought back, then yielded angrily, snapping and crackling before the inexorable thrust of steel.

festoon.definition: An ornament such as a garland or chain which hangs loosely from two tacked spots.
festoon.example1: Live oak trees, festooned with cool scarves of Spanish moss, and gnarled by a century of storms, loomed over the street.
festoon.example2: Mom pulls me behind her, then regards the man festooned in the cereal box uneasily.
festoon.example3: Presently the creepers festooned the trees less frequently and there was a scatter of pearly light from the sky down through the trees.

maxima.definition: A music note equal to two (or sometimes three) longæ; in modern notation, this is typically equivalent to eight semibreves.
maxima.example1: He’s also a big fan of the black-eyed Susan’s big brother, Rudbeckia maxima, a towering daisy that will take a range of soil conditions, including wetness.
maxima.example2: Silverman recently finished her second week of guest hosting “The Daily Show” and reaped a shiny mea culpa maxima profile in the Los Angeles Times.
maxima.example3: Another tall, ironclad native composite is the giant coneflower, Rudbeckia maxima.

dehumanization.definition: The act or process of dehumanizing.
dehumanization.example1: On slave ships, newly captured Africans were forcibly shaved in a profound act of dehumanization, an act that effectively severed the link between hair and cultural identity.
dehumanization.example2: Davis and Daisy were chatting back and forth about the dehumanization of Clone troopers, and Mychal jumped in to explain that Daisy was actually kind of a famous writer of Star Wars fan fiction.
dehumanization.example3: Dominance, even the threat of it, is a form of dehumanization.

enchanter.example1: Had the old enchanter ordered him to capture a full-grown gwythaint, Taran would gladly have set out after one of the vicious winged creatures.
enchanter.example2: Taran noticed the enchanter had even made some attempt at straightening up the disorder of ancient volumes crowding the room.
enchanter.example3: Later, he and Gwydion spent several hours alone, for there were important matters Gwydion would reveal only to the old enchanter.

pirated.definition: To appropriate by piracy, plunder at sea.
pirated.example1: Jesse’s assets were obvious, but not easily documented, unless the admissions committee wanted to check out one of his pirated music sites and watch him scarf up downloaded CDs.
pirated.example2: I know the world of pirated things—stolen videogames have no value because it’s cheaper and less risky to copy them.
pirated.example3: My life of crime started off small, selling pirated CDs on the corner.

tacitly.definition: In a tacit manner; done in silence or implied.
tacitly.example1: As I sat listening to my mother and father argue, I tacitly agreed with my father: there was no way the two religions could exist side by side in the house.
tacitly.example2: Not merely the validity of experience, but the very existence of external reality was tacitly denied by their philosophy.
tacitly.example3: He held up a hand, tacitly signaling for them to keep still.

plodding.definition: To walk or move slowly and heavily or laboriously (+ on, through, over).
plodding.example1: But all the same, Ruby, drenched, covered with mud, exhausted from plodding through the molasses muck, persevered.
plodding.example2: The procession was, as usual, somber, slow, and insufferably plodding.
plodding.example3: “See how these letters are straight up and down, plodding across the page? And at the end of each word, the last letter trails off like it’s giving out its dying breath.”

cinnabar.definition: A deep red mineral, mercuric sulfide, HgS; the principal ore of mercury; such ore used as the pigment vermilion.
cinnabar.example1: His clothes, still slightly damp from their recent washing, had returned to their usual cinnabar color.
cinnabar.example2: So he asks Theo to send him his colors: silver, white, lemon chrome yellow, vermilion, geranium lake, carmine, Prussian blue, very light cinnabar green, orange lead, emerald green, and more.
cinnabar.example3: His paintings are great impastos of pigment: chrome yellow, Prussian blue, vermilion, carmine, very light cinnabar green, emerald green, Veronese green, orange, lemon chrome yellow, geranium lake, silver white, zinc white....

moping.definition: To carry oneself in a depressed, lackadaisical manner; to give oneself up to low spirits; to pout, sulk.
moping.example1: I had been silent and moping for hours, glancing down from time to time in nervousness at the screen on my phone.
moping.example2: It was raining out, and the twins had been moping around all afternoon.
moping.example3: I’m sorry, but all this moping over an hour on the Acela?

uvula.definition: The fleshy appendage that hangs from the back of the palate, that closes the nasopharynx during swallowing.
uvula.example1: Maybe that was where the uvula thing was.
uvula.example2: You see her hand-drawn illustrations of the human mouth, the tongue, the upper and lower palates, the uvula.
uvula.example3: “Sometimes the tongue will just fall back against the soft palate and the uvula and tonsils, especially in a person who has a very small airway,” he says.

seditious.definition: Of, related to, or being involved in sedition.
seditious.example1: More basically, Jefferson simply did not regard his behavior as seditious or treasonable.
seditious.example2: He confessed to the assassination of eminent Party members, the distribution of seditious pamphlets, embezzlement of public funds, sale of military secrets, sabotage of every kind.
seditious.example3: I was, to hear him tell it, anti-American, un-American, seditious, subversive, and probably Communist.
